Machine Learning Regression

Evan Carey, created for BH Analytics

Objectives

  • Understand machine learning versus traditional approaches to inference
  • Overview of different algorithms

Overview

The purpose of this section is to go over machine learning, specifically regression, in the context of R. We will include some general concepts of machine learning as well as the specifics of a few different regression algorithms. For further reading, I highly recommend the free ebook titled ‘Introduction to Statistical Learning’ by Gareth James. A quick web search should find this book near the top of the search results. For even more in-depth coverage of machine learning algorithms, I recommend the book ‘Elements of Statistical Learning’ by Trevor Hastie (also free online!).

Machine Learning

  • Machine learning is the science of programming algorithms to learn from data.
  • Machine learning is focused on prediction - Predictive Modeling
  • Machine learning uses finite sample properties to optimize models.
  • Traditional statistics focuses on process inference - statistical inference
  • Traditional statistics often use asymptotic properties to make inference
  • In practice, there is much overlap between the disciplines…

Machine Learning Terminology

  • Target: what I want to predict
  • Inputs: The variables I am using to predict the target
  • Samples: The rows of the dataframe
  • Unsupervised Learning: Algorithms without a target
    • Clustering
    • Dimensionality Reduction
  • Supervised Learning: Algorithms using a target
    • Classification: Target is discrete
    • Regression: Target is continuous

Variance, Bias, and Over-fitting

  • Variance refers to how variables your estimates are
  • Bias refers to how accurate your estimates are
  • Think of shooting arrows at a target: Low bias means on average, you get close to the center. Low variance means your arrows are all close together
  • There is often a trade off between bias and variance.
  • Over-fitting our data: too many attempts at fitting leads to a great fit…but maybe only for this data?

How to Avoid Over-fitting?

  • Incorporate your topical knowledge when selecting features
  • The best model fits come from careful feature selection rather than automated decisions
  • Remove redundant variables (highly correlated)
  • Sensor values in your data you know to be inaccurate (Careful data cleaning)
  • Identify structure in your data and use it appropriately
    • Do you have clusters?
    • Repeated measures over time?

Prediction and the Data Generating Process

  • There is a key concept you must understand before we move forward.
  • The goal of implementing a machine learning classification approach is to describe the data generating process, so that we can create good predictions for future realizations of data from that data generating process.
  • However, we can’t see the data generating process! All we can see is past samples from the data generating process (data we have already observed)
  • So, we will try to use the data we have observed to accurately describe the data generating process.
  • Here is the important distinction:
    • I am not interested in accurately describing the data I have already observed!
    • I am interested in using that data to accurately describe the data generating process.
    • So we have to be careful to not over fit the data we can see, at the expense of having a good model for future data (ie, a good model for the data generating process)
    • We will come back to this concept later in the lecture.

Regression Overview

  • Let’s focus on regression and learn more about the machine learning approach to statistical learning.
  • In the case where our outcome (target) variable is continuous, we can use regression algorithms to predict the mean outcome.
  • We are interested in predicting the mean value of the outcome for a given unit. We sometimes called this the ‘expected value’.
  • Some examples include:
    • Costs (what is the average cost per hospitalization for certain patients?)
    • Home values (what is the average home value, considering some traits about the home)
    • Rainfall (What is the average expected amount of rainfall?)
    • Customer wait times (What is the average expected wait time for a call center?)
    • Income (What is the average amount of income someone makes?)
  • Can you think of any more examples of continuous outcomes?

Boston Housing Data

  • The outcome of interest is the home value. What is our best estimate of median home value in the absence of any other information?
  • We can start with the mean value, intercept only model…(the mean)
  • How can we decide how good our model is?
  • We can can calculate some measure of error (how wrong the model is). We could simply aggregate the errors (residuals). We often aggregate error as mean squared error.
  • As our machine learning models get better at prediction, they should have a lower MSE.
library(dplyr)
## Predict housing price.
## Best initial prediction?
Boston2 <- 
  Boston %>%
  mutate(avg_value=mean(medv))
## How much error is there in this prediction?
Boston2 <- 
  Boston2 %>%
  mutate(error=medv-avg_value)
hist(Boston2$error)

## Squared errors
Boston2 <- 
  Boston2 %>%
  mutate(squareError=(medv-avg_value)^2)
## Mean squared error
Boston2 %>%
  summarize(MeanSquareError=mean((medv-avg_value)^2))
##   MeanSquareError
## 1        84.41956

Regularized Linear Regression

  • The next family of models we will consider are called regularized linear regression.
  • This includes LASSO, Elastic Net, and Ridge regression.
  • These are penalized forms of a regular linear regression (like a logistic regression).
  • The basic idea is that we can place a penalty on the estimated coefficients from the general linear model, ‘pushing’ them towards zero.
  • If the coefficients are related to the outcome, they will ‘push’ back against our penalty.
  • The stronger the relationship (or the stronger the predictor), the stronger they will ‘push’ back.
  • The overall effect is that the coefficients are all shrunk towards zero. If the variable is not strongly related to the outcome, it will be shrunk close to zero, or possibly all the way to zero.
  • This can give us effective variable selection, where the weak variables are eliminated since their coefficients are shrunk all the way to zero.
  • Depending on how we apply the penalty, variables will either be shrunk all the way to zero (this is called the LASSO), or they will be shrunk to a small number, but still above zero (This is called ridge regression).
  • We can also apply a mixture of the two penalties, which is called the elastic net regression.
  • A natural question you might ask is, how do I pick the best model?
    • LASSO?
    • Ridge regression?
    • Elastic net (the mixture of the two)?
  • Also, how strong of a penalty should I pick?
    • A very weak penalty, so it is essential just a logistic regression?
    • A very strong penalty, so almost all the coefficients are equal to zero?
    • Maybe something in between?

Regularized Linear Regression: Elastic Net

  • We will use an implementation in the R package glmnet, which was written by the authors who originally proposed the elastic net!

  • In this implementation, there are two different parameters we can pass into the model.

    • Lambda: this is the strength of the penalty. It should be a positive number. Small values very close to 0 represent a weak penalty, which is essentially the underlying general linear model. Larger values will penalize the coefficients to be closer to zero.
    • Alpha: this is the mixing parameter. For Alpha == 1, it will fit a LASSO model. For Alpha == 0, it will fit a ridge regression. For an alpha in between, we will get an ‘elastic net’ model.

  • For this implementation, the underlying routine will pick a range of lambdas for us, and fit the model across the entire range of lambdas.

  • Just to give you an idea visually of what is going on with this model, let’s fit a few models and plot the result. I will pass in a value of 0 for alpha first, giving us a ridge regression.

  • I will use the glmnet package first. It does not accept the formula style input, so we have to actually create the model matrices and pass them in.

library(glmnet)
## establish matrices
X = model.matrix(~.-medv-1,
                 data=BostonTrain) 
Y = BostonTrain$medv 
## fit model
mod_glm <- glmnet(x = X,
                  y=Y,
                  alpha = 0)
## Explore results
plot(mod_glm,xvar = 'lambda')

## Coefficient for lambda = 0
coef(mod_glm,s=0)

Caret and the Elastic Net

  • We can use Caret to fit the model, taking advantage of the common syntax from the train function.
  • The authors of caret have gone to the trouble of identifying what parameters are needed to optimize for a wide range of machine learning classification models.
  • In the case of glmnet (elastic net), we just saw that we need to decide on two parameters:
    • Alpha
    • lambda
  • If we simply call the caret train function, we will see that the authors have populated a reasonable range of values for these parameters.
  • The train function will fit models using a combination of different parameters, then tell us how each one has performed.
  • There are more details to be explored on how caret is deciding which model is best, but we will get to that shortly.
  • Let’s fit a model first, using the defaults.
## Use caret to fit this model
mod_glmnet <- 
  train(medv~.,
        data=BostonTrain,
        method='glmnet',
        metric="RMSE")
mod_glmnet

  • That was a lot of work for not much code!
  • Caret tried a range of alpha and lambda parameters (tuning parameters), then summarized the accuracy (and kappa) for each combination of parameters.
  • Caret reports that the most accurate combination of parameters was a small lambda (the smallest), along with an alpha == 1. This is based on accuracy.
  • The default approach to resampling is the bootstrap approach (more on this next slide).
  • Here is a summary from the documentation on exactly what caret just did:

Model Validation

  • In the prior section, we just saw caret somehow used the training data (or parts of the training data) to decide on which tuning parameter combination was ideal.
  • This was actually controlled by the trainControl argument.
  • The default values included a bootstrap approach to resampling, using 25 samples of size 990 each.
    • Bootstrapping just means we sampled (with replacement) from the dataset.
  • Another commonly used option is k-folds cross validation.
    • K-folds cross validation involves splitting the data up into k discrete groups.
    • We then fit the model on all but one of those groups, and make predictions on the group we left out.
    • We repeat this k times, then summarize the results.
  • We can implement 10 fold cross validation using the following code, with 3 repeats:
## Set control parameters
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv",
                     repeats = 3,
                     number=10,
                     savePred=T)
## Use caret to fit this model
mod_glmnet <- 
  train(medv~.,
        data=BostonTrain,
        method='glmnet',
        trControl = ctrl,
        metric="RMSE")
mod_glmnet

Comparing Models

Other algorithms

  • Caret has implemented over 200 models, all easily accessible via the caret train interface.
  • Check out the caret help page to review all the different models that are available.
  • The train function will construct a reasonable range of hyperparameters for a given model, then implement a model validation technique as shown above, then report back the optimal hyperparameters.
  • Let’s fit a few more classification techniques, and see how they perform compared with the glm or glmnet.

Robust Linear Model

  • There is a form of a linear regression called ‘robust linear regression’, which uses an M-estimator.
  • This model uses an M-estimator (rather than ordinary least squares) for optimization. This estimator is robust to outliers and extreme values. It may give us a better fit here if the data has some odd outliers that are heavily influencing the overall fit.
  • Here is a link with more information if you are interested.

Random Forest

  • A popular classification algorithm is the random forest. This can also be used for regression.
  • In order to understand a random forest, you should first think about a decision tree.
  • We can consider modeling data simply by making cutpoints on our predictors, then splitting the decision of the outcome.
  • Visually, that might look like this in the context of our data:
  • If age < 40, deny credit card
  • If age > 40, then:
    • If income > 5, accept credit card
    • If income < 5, accept credit card
  • Decision trees have a very nice appeal in that they are easy to understand and visualize. You can simply make a score card, and a human could easily make a decision on whether the outcome is yes or no.
  • But they are not very accurate or flexible individually! How can we have a good model from a single decision tree? It seems unlikely.
  • But what if we created many different decision trees, based on different subsets of the data?
  • We could take random samples of the data, then get an optimal decision tree using a subset of the predictors for each sample.
  • Each individual tree isn’t that great, but perhaps the population of all those trees (the ensemble) would be good?
  • That is the intuition behind a random forest!
  • We can easily implement a random forest using caret, which in turn uses the underlying randomForest package. - The only tuning parameter is mtry, which is the number of predictors selected for each tree.
## SVM
mod_rf <- train(medv~.,
                data=BostonTrain, 
                method = 'rf',
                trControl = ctrl,
                metric="RMSE")

Score Final Model on Test Data

  • Now we have completed predictive modeling based on the training data, lets see if its actually any good on our hold-out sample.
  • For regression, we can use the postResample function to calculate R squared and MSE on the testing data.
  • We will need to use the model to make predictions, then call the postResample function.
  • Prior to any optimization, we split the data to see if we were over-fitting the sub-sample.
## Pick best model - mod_rf
## Score testing data
b_test_pred <- predict(mod_rf,BostonTest)
postResample(b_test_pred, BostonTest$medv)
##      RMSE  Rsquared       MAE 
## 3.2426077 0.8691583 2.3062140
